  <notes>
    Keyed-DI (`AddKeyedScoped&lt;IGateResolver, X&gt;(GateType.X)`) is the chosen registration shape — the orchestrator resolves `IServiceProvider.GetRequiredKeyedService&lt;IGateResolver&gt;(action.GateType)`. This avoids a strategy-factory layer and keeps DI flat.

    The contract intentionally has only ONE method — `ResolveAsync`. Pending vs synchronous resolution is encoded in `GateOutcome.GateDecision = Pending` (resolver returns immediately; task 035 sweeps Pending outcomes and timeouts them). DO NOT add a second `WaitAsync` method — the orchestrator stores `Pending` runs and resumes on external signals (Dataverse update, webhook callback, in-chat user click).

    The `GateRequest.Payload` is intentionally `JsonElement?` — resolver-specific data (e.g., Webhook URL config, in-chat card layout hint) lives there. Strongly-typed payload variants would couple the contract to resolver implementations.

    Audit obligation: every resolver MUST call `IAuditService.LogGateDecision(...)` per ADR-015 — explicit in XML doc comment on `IGateResolver.ResolveAsync`. This is the canonical audit choke point; orchestrator does NOT also log (no double-write).
  </notes>

